        <title>Storage and Organization of Resources</title>
        <contents>&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;In this unit, there are many different Internet resources to use in your own learning as well as to consider for use with your students. If you have not already created a way to save and organize Internet links and other digital resources, now is a good time to start. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/58056366_thumbnail.jpg" width="120" height="120" alt="" style="margin: 5px;" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;details&gt;&lt;summary&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Tech Tip&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You can save and organize your Internet links so that you can access them from any computer. Consider asking your colleagues where they save and access their Internet links so that you can use a bookmarking resource to share your resources and look at your colleagues’ resources. Diigo.com is a popular social bookmarking site, but by the time that you read this, there may be newer and better ways to save, organize, and share your Internet resources. Here is a link to a review of 10 popular social bookmarking sites: &lt;a href="http://www.educatorstechnology.com/2014/02/10-excellent-social-bookmarking-tools.html" title="Popular Social Bookmarking Sites" target="_blank"&gt;http://www.educatorstechnology.com/2014/02/10-excellent-social-bookmarking-tools.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
